            <bounds x="732" y="108" width="108" height="181"/>
          </child>
          <documentation>DocGen works as an integrated process between **Archi**, **DocGen**, and **WeasyPrint**. Together, these components allow you to build, format, and publish professional architecture documents directly from your ArchiMate models.

---

### **Building the Document Structure in Archi**

In Archi, you start by creating a **document structure** (called the *docGen structure*).
This structure is built using **[diagram-model-group](https://github.com/archimatetool/archi-scripting-plugin/wiki/jArchi-Collection)** and **[diagram-model-references](https://github.com/archimatetool/archi-scripting-plugin/wiki/jArchi-Collection)**.

In this structure, **each view is one of two things** (it is **not** both at once):

1. a **diagram-model-reference to an artifact** — the artifact generates the content for the document, or
2. a **diagram-model-reference to the target ArchiMate diagram** — the diagram (the “target”) is where the documentation is generated for and organized.

The **position** of the elements within the structure determines the order, nesting, and layout of the final document.

An **artifact** is essentially an **ArchiMate View**: a structured set of ArchiMate elements and their relationships, plus optional parameters and **references to JavaScript modules**.
These modules are **dynamically loaded**, so you can extend DocGen with advanced, custom behavior. Modules can also call other modules for further processing.

> **Note:** DocGen works exclusively with *visual elements* and *attributes* within the Archi model.
> It does **not** alter or extend the underlying architecture model itself, beyond relying on the standard ArchiMate meta-model.
> This ensures that your architectural data remains fully consistent, reusable, and compliant with ArchiMate standards.

---

### **Generating the Content with DocGen**

Each module can **produce content** (HTML fragments) or **add CSS** for styling.
Content can be added in two ways:

* **Static content**, written directly in *diagram-model-notes*, or
* **Dynamic content**, extracted from a view or model—for example, to build **catalogs** or **matrices**.

Every module and element contributes **CSS classes**, enabling consistent styling and later enrichment.
You can also include **Markdown**, which DocGen converts into rich, styled HTML components.

When DocGen finishes processing, it produces a **single HTML5 document** that contains all generated content, diagrams, and stylesheets.

---

### **Converting to PDF with WeasyPrint**

As a final step, DocGen uses **WeasyPrint** to convert the HTML5 file into a **PDF**.
This PDF is your deliverable—e.g., a **TOGAF-compliant report** containing the defined **artifacts**, diagrams, and formatted sections.
</documentation>
        </element>
      </folder>
